spans.text: Cross pathed , with many a gossip's foot is trod ; By cottage door where playful children run , And cats and curs
with love to fix a woman's will
Who every Sunday morn to please her sight
his oft-told gold , Whose field or orchard tempts , with all her pride , At little cost
last at fair , well pleased by chapman's stand
at stiff-backed Rob , small thoughts I ween , Ere yet another scanty month was flown To see thee wedded to the hateful clown
thee wedded to the hateful clown
Ah Sue ! when last we worked at Hodge's hay , And
these shapely limbs resemble thine , I'd stay at home and tend the household gere , Nor on the green with other lads appear
barn thick stand the sheltered stacks
no more shall give me pain
to pull the bonnet over his face
with steady look unaltered wait , Till hindmost man had passed the Churchyard gate
with steady look unaltered wait , Till hindmost man had passed the Churchyard gate
with steady look unaltered wait , Till hindmost man had passed the Churchyard gate
the door with harsh and thundering din
the coil with loud and piteous yell
